[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The opening ceremony of the 1932 Summer Olympics took place at 14:30 PDT, on Saturday, July 30, 1932, at the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] Then known as "Los Angeles Olympic Stadium".
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] As mandated by the Olympic Charter, the proceedings of this international sporting event included welcoming speeches, hoisting of the flags and the parade of nations.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] It was held in-front of a crowd of over 101,000 people in attendance, a record not broken until the Sydney 2000 Summer Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The Games were officially opened by Vice-President of the United States of America Charles Curtis.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The master of ceremonies was prominent Los Angeles journalist Bill Henry.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] He was technical director and stadium announcer.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The production team was kept in-house by the organizing committee.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The ceremony was attended by many local and foreign dignitaries.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The ceremony included a 300-person orchestra, a choir of 1,200 singers.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] They performed national anthems and Olympic anthems.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The ceremony began at exactly 2:30 pm with the introduction of vice-president Curtis entering the stadium thru the peristyle steps, accompanied by an IOC delegation.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] He was escorted to his box suite, while "Stars and Stripes forever" march played.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] Upon arrival to his suite, he greeted the crowd.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The national anthem of the United States was played.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The parade of nations then proceeded with Greece, per tradition.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] Upon completion of the parade, organizing committee President William May Garland provided opening remarks of welcome to California and the City of Los Angeles before introducing Vice President Curtis to officially open the games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] Vice President Curtis proclaimed: "In the name of the President of the United States, I proclaim open the Olympic Games of Los Angeles, celebrating the tenth olympics of the modern era".
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] As he completed his remarks, six trumpeters blared their horns from the ramparts atop the peristyle.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] A ten-cannon salute began, ten blasts to mark the opening from outside the main gates.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] Hundreds of homing pigeons were released.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The cauldron torch was lit above the Coliseum peristyle.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The chorus began to sing Walter Bradley-Keelers "Hymne Olympique", an anthem written specifically for the Xth Olympiad.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] As the anthem played, the Olympic flag was raised in the stadium.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] Robert Gordon Sproul, UCLA president provided a dedication and benediction to the games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] Next, American fencer George Calnan gave the Olympic Oath.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The chorus then sang the poem Recessional by Rudyard Kipling.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The athletes then exited the stadium, officially ending the ceremony.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The ceremony lasted two hours, 2,000 athletes, coaches, and officials from 37 nations participated.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] Also, 800 journalists, including 200 from abroad were issued press passes.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] Tickets were sold for US$3 (equivalent to US$56.02 in 2024) to the general crowd.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] It was estimated that an additional 50,000 people were not able to enter the stadium and lingered around Exposition Park.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The anthems were performed by the 1932 Los Angeles Choir and Orchestra.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The **1932 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the X Olympiad** and also known as **Los Angeles 1932**) were an international multi-sport event held from July 30 to August 14, 1932, in Los Angeles, California, United States.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The Games were held during the worldwide Great Depression, with some nations not traveling to Los Angeles as a result; 37 countries competed, compared to the 46 at the 1928 Games in Amsterdam, and even then-U.S.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] President Herbert Hoover did not attend the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The organizing committee was led by William May Garland, a local sports enthusiast and real estate developer.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Los Angeles will host the Summer Olympics for the third time in 2028, becoming the third city in the world—following London and Paris—to do so.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The selection of the host city for the 1932 Summer Olympics was made at the 23rd IOC Session in Rome, Italy, in 1923.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Remarkably, the selection process consisted of a single bid, from Los Angeles's Olympic bid Committee led by William May Garland, and as there were no bids from any other city, Los Angeles was selected by default to host the 1932 Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Los Angeles was awarded the games on April 9, 1923.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] William May Garland led the Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games (OCOG), officially titled the "Xth Olympiad Committee" with a staff of 70 employees.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The Games were originally heavily backed by local corporate interests and L.A. business elites.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] They were primarily underwritten by a US $1 million (equivalent to US $18.67 million in 2024) state bond act, the “California Olympic Bond Act of 1927″.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Later approved as "Proposition 2" by CA voters with 73% of the vote in 1928.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The OCOG raised funds from various sources.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] 1,247,580 worth of ticket sales, 42.4% of venues capacity bringing in US $1.48 million (equivalent to US $27.69 million in 2024).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The OCOG received a share of venue concessions run by a local firm at each venue bringing in sales revenue.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The OCOG charged US $2 (equivalent to US $37.35 in 2024) a day for male athletes and coaches to stay at the Olympic Village.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Lastly, corporate sponsors like, Omega, Helms Bakery and Coca-Cola provided a revenue source.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Most venues were rented out or leased at no cost to the OCOG.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The OCOG paid for the dredging of Alamitos Bay in Long Beach for rowing events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] They paid for the Olympic Village, a pool for swimming events and paid for temporary stands at city parks and golf courses used.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Including concessions, post-games equipment sales and the bond, estimates of earnings have been placed as high as US $2.7 million (equivalent to US $50.42 million in 2024).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The OCOG did not report the financial details of the Games, although contemporary newspapers stated that the Games had made a profit of US $1 million (equivalent to US $18.67 million in 2024) at closing ceremony.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Steckel and the four other committee members deployed 650 police officers dedicated to traffic control every day of the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The Chief ordered police officers to work 12-hour days and to postpone vacations.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] 150 university students assisted the police as traffic officers.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The L.A.P.D. employed 800 duly sworn police officers.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] According to the L.A.P.D.'s official site, crime was very low during the Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Automobiles were the primary method of transportation.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] A five-member traffic committee was organized by the OCOG with the Los Angeles Police Department (LAPD) and traffic management experts.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Athletes were transported in sixty eight bus carriages to competition venues and the Olympic Village in Baldwin Hills.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The OCOG urged attendees to use the red car trolleys to avoid congestion at venues, the Pacific Electric trolleys were the largest rail network in the world at the turn of the century.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Fifteen sports venues were used for the 1932 Summer Olympics.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] In order to control costs in the wake of the Great Depression, existing venues were used.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] They included two golf courses, two city parks, three public highways, and a city road.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The Swimming Stadium was the only new venue constructed for these games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The Rose Bowl, constructed in 1921, was made into a temporary velodrome for track cycling events under the auspices of the Union Cycliste Internationale (UCI).
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum, constructed in 1923, was used as the Olympic Stadium.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The Olympic Auditorium was constructed in 1924 in preparation for Los Angeles being awarded the Games; it was modified to meet the specifications of the boxing, weightlifting, and wrestling federations.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Long Beach Marine Stadium was created in 1925 when Alamitos Bay was dredged, then further dredged seven years later in time for the 1932 Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Elysian Park, the oldest city park in Los Angeles, was founded in 1886, and has been part of the Los Angeles Police Department (LAPD) training academy since 1925.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The Riviera Country Club opened in 1926 as the Los Angeles Athletic Club Golf Course and was renamed Riviera by the time of the 1932 Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Equestrian events were held in various locations.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The equestrian cross country route was designed by U.S.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Cavalry officers John Burke Barry and Sloan Doak, members of the IFE and former Olympians.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] It was known for being brutally difficult and bisecting multiple rural highways, starting from the Riviera Country Club, thru Santa Monica, West Los Angeles, the Olympic Village and ending at Sunset Fields Gold Club.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Named the "Westchester course", although the course did not enter the modern-day neighborhood boundaries of Westchester.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Dressage was held at the Riviera Country Club and show jumping at the Coliseum.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The Swimming Stadium, constructed adjacent to the Coliseum in 1932, was intended to be a temporary structure.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] LA introduced the first Olympic Village, providing housing for male athletes.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The accommodations provided in Los Angeles Baldwin Hills neighborhood is considered to be the first official modern Olympic Village, with a capacity of 2,000 people and located to the west of the city.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Consisting of a group of buildings with rooms to lodge athletes (men only), as well as providing a place to eat and train, it serves as the model for today's Olympic Villages.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] It also provided certain community services for the first time, including a hospital, a fire station, and a post office.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The Art competitions at the 1932 Summer Olympics awarded medals for works inspired by sport-related themes in five categories: architecture, literature, music, painting, and sculpture.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] American pianist Walter Bradley-Keeler composed "Hymne Olympique", an anthem written specifically for the Xth Olympiad.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The IOC would make it the official anthem before the current Olympic anthem was created in 1958.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Opening ceremony tickets were sold for US $3 (equivalent to US $56.02 in 2024) each.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Events tickets ranged between US $1 (equivalent to US $18.67 in 2024) to US $3 (equivalent to US $56.02 in 2024) per individual event.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] A US $22 (equivalent to US $410.8 in 2024) pass was available to enter the Coliseum for all events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Children's tickets were available for US $0.5 (equivalent to US $9.34 in 2024) cents for all events.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The emblem was created by Harry Muir Kurtzworth and the OCOG's in-house art department.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] It featured the coat of arms of the United States holding the Olympic rings, along with the Olympic motto Citius, Altius, Fortius (Faster, Higher, Stronger) and a laurel branch.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The main colors used were red, white and blue, representing the flag of the United States.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] For the first time, colors were assigned to each sport discipline.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Colors were used for programs, badges, athlete identifications and event venue branding.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Although not a sport discipline, the Art Festival was assigned "Mocha Brown" as the designated color.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] An Olympic mascot, Scottish Terrier Smoky, was featured for the first time in history, albeit unofficially.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The games introduced consumer culture to the Olympics, relying on local corporate sponsorships and partnerships with the Hollywood film industry of the time.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Iconic brands like Coca-Cola expanded their early Olympic presence in 1932 serving as the "official soft drink" of the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Local baked goods maker Helms Bakery provided baked food items, including Helms Olympic Bread, the "official baker"." Omega SA also debuted as the "official timekeeper" of the games; they provided one watchmaker and thirty chronographs for officials.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] The Jeffries Printing Co. was the official printing supplier for the games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] A total of 37 nations were represented at the 1932 Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] Colombia made its first appearance at the Olympic Games, and the Republic of China competed for the first time after its failed appearance at the 1924 Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1932-summer-olympics] For the first time, all discipline events were held within 16 days, 3 weekends within the opening and closing ceremonies.
