[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The Opening Ceremony of the 1980 Summer Olympics was the official opening ceremony held in the afternoon at 16:00 Moscow Time (UTC+3) on 19 July 1980 in the Grand Arena of the Central Lenin Stadium.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] It was attended by the Chairman of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of the USSR, Leonid Brezhnev, and IOC President Lord Killanin.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] Due to changes made to the Olympic charter in 1979, it became mandatory for the organizing country to demonstrate various elements of its culture during the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] While the Montréal ceremonies were simpler and more austere, Moscow's opening ceremony started a trend which changed the format of the ceremonies.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] Prior to 1976, Olympic opening ceremonies were truly "ceremonial", consisting of just the parade of nations and rituals associated with the official opening of the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] The USSR authorities wanted to put on a spectacle to impress the rest of the world, so highly produced artistic performances were included after the protocolar elements finished.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] Since then, subsequent opening ceremonies had a high level artistic programs, and it is now seen as an important aspect of the Games.
[src:1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony/1980-summer-olympics-opening-ceremony] After the Salyut 6 crew greetings the cultural performances started under the theme of the Friendship of the Peoples.
